It remains to acknowledge a few of the many obli- gations which Ι have incurred during the progress of the work. The help which I have received in regard to special points is acknowledged in the book itself. I may perhaps mention here the assistance given by Professor muys, Principal of J esus College, Oxford, in matters of Celtic, and by Mr. Mayhew in matters of English philology. To Professor York Powell I am indebted for constant encouragement and advice.

Of books, the two to which I owe the most are Haddan and Stubbs’ Councils and Ecclesiastical Documents, and Dr. W. Bright's delightful Chapters of Early English Church History. I have also learned much, especially in regard to the sources of Bede's scientific works, from Dr. Kar] &lerneus excellent monograph, Beda der Ehrwiirdige und scine Zeit.

In regard to MSS. I have to acknowledge the unvarying courtesy of their custodiaris, In Oxford I have to thank the Librarians of Balliol, Merton, N ew, Magdalen, and St. John’s Colleges 3 the officials of the Bodleian generally, and in particular the Rev. W. D. Macray, who is always ready to place his great palaeographical knowledge at the service of every student.

At Cambridge I have to thank Mr. F. Jenkinson, the University Librarian, and his assistant, Mr. Alfred Rogers, for the special kindness which they showed me when Ι was collating the famous Moore MS. of Bede.
